* {{IPA|/n, t, d/}} are [[Laminal consonant|laminal]] [[Denti-alveolar consonant|denti-alveolar]] {{IPA|[{{IPA link|n̪}}, {{IPA link|t̪}}, {{IPA link|d̪}}]}}, while {{IPA|/s, z/}} are dentalized laminal alveolar {{IPA|[{{IPA link|s̪}}, {{IPA link|z̪}}]}},{{sfnp|Khan|Lescot|1970|p=5}} pronounced with the blade of the tongue very close to the back of the upper front teeth, with the tip resting behind lower front teeth.
*Kurdish contrasts plain alveolar {{IPA|/l/}} and velarized [[postalveolar]]{{sfnp|Sedeeq|2017|p=82}} {{IPA|/ɫ/}} lateral approximants. Unlike in English, the sounds are separate phonemes rather than [[allophone]]s.{{sfnp|Rahimpour|Dovaise|2011|p=75}}
*Postvocalic {{IPA|/d/}} is [[lenition|lenited]] to an approximant {{IPAblink|ð̞}}. This is a regional feature occurring in other Iranian languages as well and called by Windfuhr the "Zagros d".{{sfnp|Windfuhrt|2012|p=597}}
*Kurdish has two [[rhotic consonant|rhotic]] sounds; the [[alveolar flap]] ({{IPA|/ɾ/}}) and the [[alveolar trill]] ({{IPA|/r/}}). While the former is alveolar, the latter has an [[alveo-palatal]] articulation.{{sfnp|Rahimpour|Dovaise|2011|pp=75-76}}
*According to {{Harvcoltxt|Hamid|2015}}, {{IPA|/x, xʷ, ɣ, ɣʷ/}} are uvular {{IPA|[{{IPA link|χ}}, χʷ, {{IPA link|ʁ}}, ʁʷ]}} in Central Kurdish.{{sfnp|Hamid|2015|p=18}}
*Northern Kurdish distinguishes between aspirated and unaspirated [[voiceless stop]]s, which can be aspirated in all positions. Thus {{IPA|/p/}} contrasts with {{IPA|/pʰ/}}, {{IPA|/t/}} with {{IPA|/tʰ/}}, {{IPA|/k/}} with {{IPA|/kʰ/}}, {{IPA|/q/}} with {{IPA|/qʰ/}}, and the affricate {{IPA|/t͡ʃ/}} with {{IPA|/t͡ʃʰ/}}.{{sfnp|Haig|Matras|2002|p=5}}{{sfnp|Rahimpour|Dovaise|2011|p=75}}{{sfnp|Campbell|King|2000|p=899}}
*Although {{IPAblink|ɥ}} is considered an allophone of {{IPA|/w/}}, some phonologists argue that it should be considered a phoneme.{{sfnp|Fattahi|Anonby|Gheitasi|2016}}
*Kurdish distinguishes between the plain {{IPA|/s/}} and {{IPA|/z/}} and the velarized {{IPA|/sˠ/}} and {{IPA|/zˠ/}}. These velarized counterparts are less emphatic than the Semitic [[emphatic consonant]]s.{{sfnp|Fattah|2000|pp=96-97}}{{sfnp|McCarus|1958|pp=12}}
*{{IPAblink|ɲ}} is an allophone of {{IPA|/n/}} in Southern Kurdish, occurring in the about 11 to 19 words that have the consonant group {{angbr|nz}}. The word ''yânza'' is pronounced as {{IPA|[jɑːɲzˠa]}}.{{sfnp|Fattah|2000|pp=97-98}}

===Labialization===
*Kurdish has labialized counterparts to the velar plosives, the voiceless velar fricative and the uvular stop. Thus {{IPA|/k/}} contrasts with {{IPA|/kʷ/}}, {{IPA|/ɡ/}} with {{IPA|/ɡʷ/}}, {{IPA|/x/}} with {{IPA|/xʷ/}}, and {{IPA|/q/}} with {{IPA|/qʷ/}}.{{sfnp|Gündoğdu|2016|pp=61-62}} These labialized counterparts do not have any distinct letters or [[Digraph (orthography)|digraph]]. Examples are the word ''xulam'' ('servant') which is pronounced as {{IPA|[xʷɪˈlɑːm]}}, and ''qoç'' ('horn') is pronounced as {{IPA|[qʷɨnd͡ʒ]}}.{{sfnp|Gündoğdu|2016|p=65}}

===Palatalization===
*After {{IPA|/ɫ/}}, {{IPA|/t/}} is palatalized to {{IPA|[tʲ]}}. An example is the Central Kurdish word ''gâlta'' ('joke'), which is pronounced as {{IPA|[gɑːɫˈtʲæ]}}.{{sfnp|Rahimpour|Dovaise|2011|p=75}}
*{{IPA|/k/}} and {{IPA|/ɡ/}} are strongly palatalized before the front vowels {{IPA|/i/}} and {{IPA|/e/}} as well as {{IPAblink|ɥ}}, becoming acoustically similar to {{IPA|/t͡ʃ/}} and {{IPA|/d͡ʒ/}}.{{sfnp|Haig|Matras|2002|p=5}}
*When preceding {{IPA|/ŋ/}}, {{IPA|/s, z/}} are palatalized to {{IPA|/ʒ/}}. In the same environment, {{IPA|/ʃ/}} also becomes {{IPA|/ʒ/}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kurdish language i. History of the Kurdish language|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/kurdish-language-i|website=Iranicaonline|accessdate=6 December 2017}}</ref>

===Pharyngealization===
*In some cases, {{IPA|/p, t, k, s, z/}} are [[pharyngealized]] to {{IPA|[pˤ, tˤ, kˤ, sˤ, zˤ]}}. For example, the word ''sed/ṣed'' is pronounced as {{IPA|[ˈsˤɛd]}}{{sfnp|Rahimpour|Dovaise|2011|p=75}}{{sfnp|Thackston|2006a|pp=1-2}}{{sfnp|Thackston|2006b|pp=2-4}}
*Furthermore, while {{IPA|[fˤ]}} and {{IPA|[ɡˤ]}} are unique to Central Kurdish,{{sfnp|Asadpour|Mohammadi|2014|p=109}} Northern Kurdish has {{IPA|[t͡ʃˤ]}}.{{sfnp|Thackston|2006b|p=2}}

===Facultative consonants===
*{{IPA|/ħ/}} and {{IPA|/ɣ/}} are non-native phonemes that are mostly present in words of Arabic origin. Even though they are usually replaced by {{IPA|/h/}} and {{IPA|/x/}} respectively, they are facultative. Thus the word ''heft/ḧeft'' ('seven' {{IPA|/ˈħɛft/}}) can be pronounced as either {{IPA|[ˈhɛft]}} or {{IPA|[ˈħɛft]}}, and ''xerîb/ẍerîb'' ('stranger', {{IPA|/ɣɛˈriːb/}}) as either {{IPA|[xɛˈriːb]}} or {{IPA|[ɣɛˈriːb]}}.{{sfnp|Khan|Lescot|1970|p=6}}
*{{IPA|/ʕ/}} is only present in words of Arabic and Persian origin and is only present in initial position.{{sfnp|Asadpour|Mohammadi|2014|p=114}} An Arabic loanword like "Hasan" would thus be pronounced as {{IPA|/ʕɛˈsɛn/}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=1.26 Pharyngeal substitution |website=Dialects of Kurdish |url=http://kurdish.humanities.manchester.ac.uk/pharyngeal-substitution/ |publisher=University of Manchester|accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref> The phoneme is absent in some Northern and Southern Kurdish dialects.<ref>{{cite web|title=1.27 Pharyngeal retention in ‘animal’|url=http://kurdish.humanities.manchester.ac.uk/pharyngeal-retentionloss-animal/ |website=Dialects of Kurdish |publisher=University of Manchester|accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref>

==Vowels==
The vowel inventory differs by dialect, some dialect having more vowel phonemes than others. {{IPA|/iː, ʊ, uː, ɛ, eː, oː, ɑː/}} are the only vowel phonemes present in all three Kurdish dialects.
