{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}} {{Infobox writer |name = Rachel Held Evans |image = rachel-held-evans.jpg |birth_name = Rachel Grace Held |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1981|6|8}} |occupation = {{hlist |Columnist |author}} |nationality = American |genre = Christian |website = {{URL|http://rachelheldevans.com}} }}
'''Rachel Held Evans''' (née '''Rachel Grace Held''', June 8, 1981) is an American Christian columnist, blogger and author. Her book ''A Year of Biblical Womanhood'' was on ''[[The New York Times]]''{{'}} e-book non-fiction best-seller list.<ref>{{cite web |title=Best Sellers - The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2012-11-18/e-book-nonfiction/list.html |accessdate=February 9, 2015}}</ref>
==Life and career== Evans was born to Peter and Robin Held. She grew up in [[Birmingham, Alabama]]. At age 14, she and her family moved to [[Dayton, Tennessee]], where her father took an administrative position at [[Bryan College]]. She attended [[Rhea County High School]] and then went to Bryan College where she majored in English literature. She received her Bachelor of Arts degree in 2003 and married her college boyfriend, Dan Evans, that year. They moved to [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]], where she worked as an intern for the ''[[Chattanooga Times Free Press]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alumna Rachel Held Evans - published, working and improving |work=The Bryan College Triangle |date=October 23, 2013 |url=http://www.bryantriangle.com/features/alumna-rachel-held-evans-published-working-and-improving/ |accessdate=January 7, 2014}}</ref>
In 2004, Evans returned to Dayton where she worked full-time for the local paper, ''The Herald-News''. In 2006, she transitioned from full-time to writing [[pro bono]] as the paper's humor columnist; in 2007, she won an award for "Best Personal Humor Column" from the Tennessee Press Association.<ref name="tpa_award">{{cite web |title = 2007 University of Tennessee - Tennessee Press Association - State Press Contests Awards|page = 14|format = PDF (press clippings)|year = 2007|url = http://www.tnpress.com/TTParchive/ttp8.07awards.pdf|accessdate = June 6, 2012}}</ref> She continued to write freelance articles for national publications and started a blog.<ref name="todayshow">{{cite web | last = Evans | first = Rachel Held | title = Living through 'A Year of Biblical Womanhood' | date = October 22, 2012 | work = Today Books
| url = http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/49477743/ns/today-books/t/living-through-year-biblical-womanhood/ | accessdate = November 6, 2012 }}</ref>
In September 2008, Evans signed with [[Zondervan]] for her first book, ''Evolving in Monkey Town''.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Evolving in Monkey Town: How a Girl Who Knew All the Answers Learned to Ask the Questions |last=Evans |first=Rachel Held |publisher=Zondervan |year=2010 |isbn=9780310293996}}</ref> The book explores her journey from religious certainty to a faith which accepts doubt and questioning; the title is based on the [[Scopes Monkey Trial]] that occurred in Dayton.<ref>{{cite web |title=Evolving in Monkey Town |work=''RachelHeldEvans.com'' |url=http://rachelheldevans.com/monkey-town/ |accessdate=November 6, 2012}}</ref> Her second book, ''A Year of Biblical Womanhood: How a Liberated Woman Found Herself Sitting on Her Roof, Covering Her Head, and Calling Her Husband Master'', was released in October 2012.<ref>{{Cite news |title=A Year of Biblical Womanhood |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/double_x/doublex/2011/09/a_year_of_biblical_womanhood.html |newspaper=Slate |date=September 1, 2011 |access-date=August 21, 2015 |issn=1091-2339 |first=Ruth |last=Graham}}</ref><ref name="huffpost">{{cite web |last=Compton |first=Allie |title=Rachel Held Evans, Author of "A Year of Biblical Womanhood", Spent a Year Living the Bible Literally |date=October 23, 2012 |work=HuffPost |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/10/23/a-year-of-biblical-womanhood_n_2006184.html}}</ref> She recounts how she spent an entire year of living a Biblical lifestyle literally. The book also garnered national media attention for Evans as she appeared on ''[[The Today Show]]''.<ref name="todayshow"/> In 2014, Evans re-released ''Evolving in Monkey Town'' with the new title of ''Faith Unraveled''.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Faith Unraveled: How a Girl Who Knew All the Answers Learned to Ask Questions |last=Evans |first=Rachel Held |publisher=Zondervan |year=2014 |isbn=9780310339168}}</ref>
In 2015, she wrote a column in ''[[The Washington Post]]'' that was entitled: "Want millennials back in the pews? Stop trying to make church 'cool'”. In the column she self-identified as a [[Millennials|millennial]], and expressed her belief that while churches in the United States are attempting to get more millennials in the church, their approach is wrong because they focus primarily on stylistic aspects, which she believes "are not the key to drawing millennials back to God in a lasting and meaningful way. Young people don’t simply want a better show." She believes that while the church is acting in good faith in their efforts to bring millennials back to the church, they too frequently use misguided strategies to do so.<ref name="Millennial Mission">{{Cite journal |last=Devlin |first=Nathanael |title=Millennial Mission: The Transmission of Christianity Is Not a New Task. |url=http://web.a.ebscohost.com/ehost/pdfviewer/pdfviewer?vid=1&sid=781e0df8-fe3a-480c-8973-a793f89c0b23%40sdc-v-sessmgr05 |format=PDF |journal=[[Touchstone: A Journal of Mere Christianity]] |type=Article |language=en-US |location=Pennsylvania |publication-place=Chicago |date=Spring 2018 |volume=31 |issue=2 |pages=42–45 |issn=0897-327X |id=128120637 |access-date=2018-10-11 |subscription=yes |lay-url=http://web.a.ebscohost.com/ehost/detail/detail?vid=0&sid=0575d016-0c81-43d6-a939-a8362aa91f5b%40sessionmgr4006&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZQ%3d%3d#AN=128120637&db=aph |via=Academic Search Premier}}</ref>
Evans is an [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalian]]<ref>{{Cite web |title=Rachel Held Evans defends exit from evangelicalism, calls Christians to celebrate sacraments |url=http://jonathanmerritt.religionnews.com/2015/03/09/rachel-held-evans-defends-exit-evangelicalism-calls-christians-celebrate-sacraments/ |website=Religion News Service: On Faith & Culture |accessdate=August 21, 2015 |last=Merritt |first=Jonathan |date=March 9, 2015}}</ref> and attends [[St. Luke's Episcopal Church (Cleveland, Tennessee)|St. Luke's Episcopal Church in Cleveland, Tennessee]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=How Rachel Held Evans became the most polarizing woman in evangelicalism |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/acts-of-faith/wp/2015/04/16/how-rachel-held-evans-became-the-most-polarizing-woman-in-evangelicalism/ |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=April 16, 2015 |access-date=August 21, 2015 |issn=0190-8286 |first=Sarah Pulliam |last=Bailey}}</ref> She no longer considers herself to be an [[Evangelicalism|evangelical]] due to its close association with the [[Christian right]] in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/religion/article/76494-ex-evangelical-rachel-held-evans-on-feminism-and-the-bible.html|title=Ex-Evangelical Rachel Held Evans Still Cherishes Her Bible|work=Publishers Weekly|access-date=September 26, 2018}}</ref> In early August 2016, Evans published an editorial for ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'' defending her "[[pro-life]] Christian" position and support for [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] presidential nominee [[Hillary Clinton]] in the 2016 U.S. presidential election.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Held Evans |first1=Rachel |title=I'm a pro-life Christian. Here's why I'm voting for Hillary Clinton. |url=https://www.vox.com/2016/8/4/12369912/hillary-clinton-pro-life |accessdate=January 20, 2017 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |date=August 4, 2016}}</ref>
==Books== {{refbegin|}} * {{cite book|ref={{harvid|Evans|2010}}|last=Evans|first=Rachel Held|title=Evolving in Monkey Town: How a Girl Who Knew All the Answers Learned to Ask the Questions|publisher=[[Zondervan]]|year=2010|nopp=y|isbn=978-0310293996|authormask=1}}, republished as {{cite book|ref={{harvid|Evans|2014}}|last=Evans|first=Rachel Held|title=Faith Unraveled: How a Girl Who Knew All the Answers Learned to Ask Questions|publisher=[[Zondervan]]|year=2014|nopp=y|isbn=978-0310339168|authormask=1}} * {{cite book|ref={{harvid|Evans|2012}}|last=Evans|first=Rachel Held|title=A Year of Biblical Womanhood: How a Liberated Woman Found Herself Sitting on Her Roof, Covering Her Head, and Calling Her Husband Master|publisher=[[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson]]|year=2012|pages=352|nopp=y|isbn=978-1595553676|authormask=1}} * {{cite book|ref={{harvid|Evans|2015}}|last=Evans|first=Rachel Held|title=Searching for Sunday: Loving, Leaving, and Finding the Church|year=2015|publisher=[[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson]]|isbn=978-0718022129|authormask=1}} * {{Cite book|title=Inspired: Slaying Giants, Walking on Water, and Loving the Bible Again|last=Evans|first=Rachel Held|publisher=[[Thomas Nelson, Inc.]]|year=2018|isbn=9781400211074|location=|nopp=y|author-mask=1}}
